The Problem
The Process
People are struggling to find grocery stores selling goods that fit both their financial and dietary needs. The inefficiency of traditional grocery shopping has people seeking a better online alternative.

01 Empathize
02 Define
03 Ideate
05 Validate
4 People, 2 men and 2 women, ranging 28 - 45 years old, were interviewed. This interview provided perspectives on what issues they had with online grocery shopping with a 3 users citing the struggle to find affordable items.
The userbase we are designing for is millennial-aged working adults who are looking for a wide range of dietary choices while looking to minimize the time spent buying groceries.
User Interveiws
Personas
User Flow
Based on the feedback from the interviews the biggest problem is that users were not able to find what they wanted on different apps. This influenced a straight forward approach to the user flow through the app while still allowing users the option to backtrack or skip to different parts of the process when needed.
Low, mid and Hi-fidelity wireframes were made for the prototype. Features such as filters, a search function and a price range slider were included. I decided adding the price range slider could clutter the screen and overwhelm users leading to the filter option being chosen.
Swiftness, efficiency, the idea of being able to reach everyone were the focal points of inspiration for the design. The parachute encompasses the ideas of reachability and efficiency with the motion lines implying urgency and swiftness. With the bags with groceries identify what the focus of the business.
Sample questions asked during user interviews:
1. How many times have you used the Grocery App compared to traditional shopping?

2. If you wanted to add organic ingredients to your cart, how would you proceed?

3. If you decided mid way through shopping you wanted to make a completely different order how would you remove the current items from your cart?

MEASURING SUCCESS
NEXT STEPS
LESSONS LEARNED
To understand whether this MVP will be successful or not will have to do with the number of users, their activity, and their demographic. Is the product being used? How? By who?

Once these factors are determined, we can dictate which features are worth iterating upon. This also opens up the discussion of whether or not this app should be marketed for not only grocery shopping but eventually something similar for fast food or other essentials.
1. Depending on the success rate, design the nest iteration with options for pick up and run another usability test.

2. Tailor which features that need to be enhanced and which need to be removed

3. Design a screen for delivery review.
User interviews and casual conversations proved to me that this app is not just for people looking for a convenient way to buy groceries. It is a way for people to support themselves and dependents while dealing with the overwhelming challenges they face daily.

A user-centered design does not mean to design for users only. Creating an identity for the brand that people are attracted to, making a design that can be easily understood by other teams and improved upon by future designers.
